ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"
eval "$(ssh-agent -s)" (in another terminal)
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub (public key)


4. Add the Public Key to GitHub
Log into your GitHub account.

Navigate to Settings (profile photo menu).

In the sidebar, click SSH and GPG keys.

Click New SSH key or Add SSH key.

Provide a descriptive Title for the key (e.g., "Work Laptop").

Paste the content of your public key into the Key field.

Click Add SSH key.

5. Add the Public Key to GitLab
Log into your GitLab account.

Select your avatar in the upper-right corner.

Select Edit profile or Settings.

In the left sidebar, select SSH Keys.

Click Add new key.

Paste the content of your public key into the Key box.

Provide a descriptive Title.

Click Add key.


. Test the Connection
After adding the key to each service, test the connection to verify authentication:

GitHub: ssh -T git@github.com

Expected success message: Hi username! You've successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access.

GitLab: ssh -T git@gitlab.com

Expected success message: Welcome to GitLab, @username!
